This being so, we should not be surprised to find distinet traces of Tacitus' acquaintance with Seneca in the Dialogus. And accord- ingly Peter,¹⁸⁸ starting out with this presumption, recognises this influence “in der Freiheit, mit welcher, wie unser Verfasser, so auch Seneca, nur in viel ausgedehnterem Maasse als dieser, dem Sprachgebrauch Gewalt anthut, um den Ausdruclr bezeichnender und ausdrucksvoller zu macheu '' and in Seneca’s fondness for epiprammetic expressions.Iol Now it is curious to observe that in the many illustratione given by Peter of Seneca's stylistic audacity, the Dialogus either furnishes no analogous usage or, where it does, the expression is neither peculiar¹⁹⁰ to Seneca, nor in any way characteristic. The same criticism holds good of the formidabis array of evidence accumulated by Kleiber.¹⁰¹ For of the 64 in- stances of stylistic parallelisms between the Dialogus and the writings of Seneca cited, there is aot a siayle phrase which can confidently be regarded as a genuine reminiscence. For even in the case of some synonymis collocations like emendatus et com- positus (Ep. 4,1 Dial. c. 412) or quietum compositumque (Ep. 100,8 Dial. c. 36 h), which apparently do not occur elsewhere, it were extremely rash to assert, in view of the demonstrable fondness for similar fullness of expression, not only in the minor works of Tacitus, but in Latin writers generally, that they were taken directly.from Seneca! The other instances present at best but a very remote resemblance, whether in thought or diction, or they are of frequent occurrence elsewhere, or purely commonplace and nondescript.¹⁹²
